{"id":"1508.03665","submitter":"Sahil Agarwal","authors":"Sahil Agarwal and J. S. Wettlaufer","title":"Maximal Stochastic Transport in the Lorenz Equations","comments":"6 pages, 5 figures","journal-ref":"Phys. Lett. A Vol 380, 142 (2016)","doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"nlin.CD math-ph math.DS math.MP","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We calculate the stochastic upper bounds for the Lorenz equations using an\nextension of the background method. In analogy with Rayleigh-B\\'enard\nconvection the upper bounds are for heat transport versus Rayleigh number. As\nmight be expected, the stochastic upper bounds are larger than the\ndeterministic counterpart of \\citet{Doering15}, but their variation with noise\namplitude exhibits interesting behavior. Below the transition to chaotic\ndynamics the upper bounds increase monotonically with noise amplitude. However,\nin the chaotic regime this monotonicity depends on the number of realizations\nin the ensemble; at a particular Rayleigh number the bound may increase or\ndecrease with noise amplitude. The origin of this behavior is the coupling\nbetween the noise and unstable periodic orbits, the degree of which depends on\nthe degree to which the ensemble represents the ergodic set. This is confirmed\nby examining the close returns plots of the full solutions to the stochastic\nequations and the numerical convergence of the noise correlations. The\nnumerical convergence of both the ensemble and time averages of the noise\ncorrelations is sufficiently slow that it is the limiting aspect of the\nrealization of these bounds. Finally, we note that the full solutions of the\nstochastic equations demonstrate that the effect of noise is equivalent to the\neffect of chaos.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 14 Aug 2015 21:10:21 GMT"}],"update_date":"2020-07-06"}
